\section*{Understanding Language Acquisition}
* Noam Chomsky $(1968,1978,1991)$, a linguist argued that humans are born with an innate linguistic capability that emerges primarily as a function of maturation. According to his analysis, all the world's languages even for deaf children, share a similar underlying structure. Chomsky suggests that the human brain has a neural system, the language-acquisition device, that both permits the understanding of the structure of language and provides strategies and techniques for learning the unique characteristics of a given native language.
* The learning-theory approach suggests that language acquisition follows the principles of reinforcement and conditioning discussed in Chapter 5. For example, a child who utters the word "mama" is hugged and praised by her mother, which reinforces the behaviour and makes its repetition more likely. This view suggests that children first learn to speak by being rewarded for making sounds that approximate speech. Ultimately, through a process of shaping, language becomes more and more like adult speech (Skinner, 1957).
- Canada has two official languages but there are many languages spoken by Canadians. Bilinguals have distinct advantages compared to monolinguals. See Exploring Diversity and Pathways Through Psychology sections.
* The learning theory approach is less successful when it comes to explaining the acquisition of language rules. Children are reinforced not only when they use proper language, but also when they respond incorrectly.

Canadian teachers have used the whole language approach, the basic skills approach, or a combination of the two.
* The whole language approach stresses the use of whole and meaningful materials. This 'top-down' processing means that children develop a story orally. Then the teacher prints the story and they read it.
* The basic skills approach emphasizes the recognition of words in isolation. This 'bottom-up' processing means that the children learn the rules, the sound units into words and then the words into sentences.
* Research by Betty Ann Levy, McMaster University indicates both basic skills and whole language approaches contribute to reading acquisition.
* Levy and Lysynchuk (1997) instructed one group of beginning readers in the acquisition of an initial word set using whole language approach. They instructed a second group using the basic skills approach. They found that word set was learned more quickly and accurately by readers instructed by the basic skills approach than by the whole language approach. Also, they found that the thoroughness by which the children learned the word set determined how well they read new words. Single word practice enabled the children to read stories with these words more quickly and with better comprehension.
